Permissions - rwxrwxrwx
  To set execute permission, use commmand 'chmod 755 Hello_script.sh'. 755 will set the permissions as follows.

    Please note that, abc (here 755) will set the permission in the following order. OWNER GROUP OTHER.
    so 7 will set permission for owner, 5 for group, 5 for other.
    7 in binary is 111, so rwx i.e. read write execute are all set to 1. Think of it as 1 means switch on , so setting 1 to read write execute means that owner has the ability, or these permissions are on for owner.
    5 in binary is 101, so the group will only have read and execute permission on the script. They can't modify it.
    Same goes for others.
    Since we are talking about it , I want you to execute the following command on your terminal, just type ls -l. This command will list files and directories (no hidden file or directory will be shown, to view hidden directories or files as well use ls -al) present in your working directory (the directory you are in) along with their permissions , owner, and date on which they were modified.
    let say a file have following permissions, -rwxr-xr-x, here rwx is for owner , i.e. the owner can read, write(modify), execute that file. group have r-x that means they can read and execute the file but can not write to it. Same goes for others.


Other Special Variables -
There are a few other variables that the system sets for you to use as well.

    $0 - The name of the Bash script.
    $1 - $9 - The first 9 arguments to the Bash script. (As mentioned above.)
    $# - How many arguments were passed to the Bash script.
    $@ - All the arguments supplied to the Bash script.
    $? - The exit status of the most recently run process.
    $$ - The process ID of the current script.
    $USER - The username of the user running the script.
    $HOSTNAME - The hostname of the machine the script is running on.
    $SECONDS - The number of seconds since the script was started.
    $RANDOM - Returns a different random number each time is it referred to.
    $LINENO - Returns the current line number in the Bash script. 


wget - Download file : wget <download_target_url>
scp (secure copy) - Transferring files from your host. This command allows you to transfer files between two computers using SSH protocol to provide both authentication and encryption.
  from local to remote -> scp <local_file> target_user@target_ip:<path_to_store_the_file_at>
  from remote to local -> scp remote_user@remote_ip:<path_of_the_file> <path/name_to_save_as>

serving file from your host - WEB : python3 -m http.server <port>, run this in the directory that you want to host on web.
    -> Simultaneously, we can use wget for e.g, wget http://MACHINE_IP:<port>/<file_to_download>

